Although based on a similar approach, the action of a ${\rm{SRD}^{mc}}$ collision operator and a standard SRD collision operator on the particle velocities are not fully equivalent. The latter collision operator employs a fixed rotation angle while the rotation angle in the former operator is determined in every collision cell from the color action principle as explained in Sec.~\ref{ssec:multiphase}. Angular momentum conservation will cause an additional departure from the dynamic viscosity of the SRD fluid given by the closed form expressions for $\eta$ eqn.~\eqref{eq:kinvisc}.

Differences between the measured dynamic viscosities of the ${\rm{SRD}^{mc}_{-}}$ or ${\rm{SRD}^{mc}_{+}}$ fluid, and the viscosity of a standard SRD fluid can be quantified using the concept of an ``equivalent'' rotation angle $\alpha_{\rm E}$ such that  $\eta_{SRD}(\alpha_{\rm E})$ according to eqn.~\eqref{eq:kinvisc} equals the measured viscosity $\eta_{{\rm{SRD}^{mc}}}$. This equivalent angle depends on the average number $\left\langle N_{\xi} \right\rangle$ of the fluid particles and the temperature $T$. Within our tested parameter range the equivalent collision angle for ${\rm{SRD}^{mc}_{-}}$ is $\alpha_{\rm E}=(92.5\pm 2.9)^{\circ}$, whereas for ${\rm{SRD}^{mc}_{+}}$ it is lowered to $\alpha_{E}=(58.8\pm 1.4)^{\circ}$. This simply means that a mono--phase ${\rm{SRD}^{mc}_{-}}$ fluid is comparable to a standard SRD fluid with a fixed rotation angle of $\alpha\approx90^{\circ}$ and a ${\rm{SRD}^{mc}_{+}}$ fluid is comparable to a standard SRD fluid with a fixed rotation angle of $\alpha\approx60^{\circ}$, respectively. Also this finding complies perfectly to collisional dominated systems (see e.g.~\cite{Ihle2001,Ihle2003a,Gompper2008}). In this regime, the viscosity can be modified by changing the particle mass $m$ and, as we have shown, can easily be measured e.g. by a linear shear flow experiment. In a multi--phase system individual viscosities can be employed by assigning different mass $m_c$ to the fluid particles of each phase color $c$. Control over the viscosities of each single fluid phase allows us to study a wide range of problems in immiscible two--phase flows and soft condensed matter in general.






\section{Two--phase systems}
\label{sec:twophase}

Having determined the mono--phase properties of the ${\rm{SRD}^{mc}}$ collision operator, we will now proceed to the substantially more complex situation of immiscible two--phase flow. Multi--phase flows in general are governed by an interplay of inertial, viscous and capillary forces. To determine the relative magnitude of these forces requires precise measurements not only of the bulk phase viscosity but also of the interfacial tension $\gamma$ between the fluid phases. A relation of the interfacial tension $\gamma$ between ${\rm{SRD}^{mc}}$ fluids to the fundamental simulation parameters average particle number $\left\langle N_{\xi} \right\rangle$, temperature $T$, and the weights $\kappa_{cc^\prime}$ of phase colors $c,\,c^\prime$ in the collision operator is mandatory. In the following section, we will present three independent approaches to determine the interfacial tension of two coexisting phases of a ${\rm{SRD}^{mc}_{+}}$ fluid.




\subsection{Interfacial tension -- planar interface}
\label{ssec:planar}

In equilibrium the mechanical tension of a fluid--fluid interface can be expressed by an integral over the stresses in the two adjacent fluid bulk phases. Provided identical pressures in the two adjacent bulk phases, which is the case for a planar interface, we can apply the Kirkwood--Buff formula \cite{Kirkwood1949,Rowlinson1982} to calculate the interfacial tension $\gamma$ as an excess stress:

